==Distribution==
Bay-breasted warblers breed in the [[Taiga|boreal]] spruce-fir forests of eastern and central [[Canada]] (Newfoundland, west to northeastern British Columbia), as well as the far northeast of the [[United States]].<ref name="Curson"/><ref name=Sibley/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ebird.org/species/babwar|title=Bay-breasted Warbler - eBird}}</ref> The species winters in the wet lowland forests of northeastern [[South America]], the [[Caribbean]], and southern Central America, and may be seen during spring and fall migration across the eastern half of the United States in a variety of vegetative communities. Many individuals cross the Gulf of Mexico on their long-distance migration, although some travel north and south along the Mexican shore.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Bay-breasted_Warbler/|title=Bay-breasted Warbler - All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology}}</ref> It is a rare vagrant west to the west coast of North America, and has also been recorded in Greenland.<ref name="Curson"/><ref name=Sibley />

==Behaviour and ecology==
===Food and feeding===
In the breeding season, bay-breasted warblers feed primarily on insects and spiders, especially the [[spruce budworm]] (''Choristoneura fumiferana'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/bay-breasted-warbler|title=Bay-breasted Warbler - Audubon Field Guide|date=13 November 2014 }}</ref> These are gleaned from vegetation, never caught on the wing. To avoid competition with similar species, bay-breasted warblers concentrate their foraging on the breeding grounds to the interior middle portions of coniferous trees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/stanfordbirds/text/essays/MacArthur%27s_Warblers.html|title=MacArthur's Warblers|website=web.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> On wintering grounds in the tropics, fruit forms a majority of the diet. Wintering bay-breasted warblers often form mixed-species flocks with other [[Neotropical realm|neotropical]] migrants and resident species. These flocks seek food in the forest canopy, and the bay-breasted warbler is often an aggressive member of the unit, [[Mobbing (animal behavior)|bullying]] smaller species from potential food sources.<ref name=":0" />
[[File:Bay-breasted Warbler by Dan Pancamo 4.jpg|thumb|right|Female]]

===Breeding===
Nests are typically constructed in the lower portion of a [[spruce]] or [[fir]] tree. The nest is cup-shaped and primarily composed of plant material, with spider silk often utilized as well. Average clutch size is 4–7 whitish eggs with dark spots. The young are [[Altriciality|altricial]] at birth, with limited down.<ref name=":0" />

==Conservation==
The bay-breasted warbler is currently classified by the IUCN as [[least concern]], with an increasing population. Historically, though, the species has been slowly declining, with a loss of insect prey and global climate change contributing factors to decline. The global population is estimated to be 9.9 million mature individuals.<ref name="iucn status"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pif.birdconservancy.org/ACAD/Database.aspx|title=Partners in Flight RMBO|website=pif.birdconservancy.org|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>

